Peel and finely dice the @onion{1}(peeled and finely diced). Cut the core out of each pepper then slice the @red pepper{1/2}(sliced lengthways into thin slices) and @yellow pepper{1/2}(sliced lengthways into thin slices). Now dice the pepper slices finely, coarsely chop the @coriander{3/4}(coarsely chopped) and cut the @green beans{1}(cut in half) in half.

== Roti ==

For the roti, place the @wholemeal flour{100%g} in a #bowl{} with 3/4 of the coriander. Make a well in the centre and put in the @ghee{2%tbsp} (reserving a little to brush on later). Add 3-4 tbsps of warm water & gradually form into a soft dough. Knead lightly then leave to rest in a warm place.

> The remaining coriander will be used for garnish.

== Curry ==

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a #pan{} on medium heat. Cook the chopped onion & 3/4 of the peppers with @salt{1/2%tsp}. After ~{5%minutes}, add the @curry powder mix{2%tbsps}.

> If you like your food less spicy, add less curry powder & adjust at the end.

Drain and rinse the @organic lentils{1}(drained and rinsed thoroughly). Add drained lentils, 1/2 the @vegetable stock pot{1/2} and 150ml of water. Add in the green beans & simmer for a further ~{5%minutes} with a #lid{} on.

Add the @tomato puree{1}.

Stir in the @ground almond{1/2} and take the pan off heat.

To make your roti, heat a large #frying pan{} over a high heat. Form the dough into 4 small balls and press them into thin, flat pancakes using your hands. Place directly on a very lightly oiled pan and cook on high heat until the bread begins to puff up and become lightly coloured.

Top the curry with the remaining raw pepper and a dollop of @plain yoghurt{1/2}. Serve your roti on the side and brush them with any remaining ghee. Garnish with a sprinkle of remaining coriander.

> Studies show it's important to get a good dose of protein, ideally every meal of the day, as it's our primary source of long-lasting energy. This simple recipe for lentil curry includes ground almond as well so you get a double hit of energy packed nutrition.